==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abaisse|lang=enm}}, {{term|abesse|lang=enm}}, {{term|abessen|lang=enm}}, {{term|abaishen|lang=enm}}, {{term|abassen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{term|abaisser|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|abaissier||bring low|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|a-|lang=fro}} + {{term|baissier||to lower}}, from {{etyl|VL.|en}} {{m|la|abbassiāre||to lower}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{term|bassus||short of stature, low, humble}}.<ref>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ə.ˈbeɪs/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-abase.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|eɪs|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|abas|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|archaic|lang=en}} To [[lower]] physically or [[depress]]; to [[stoop]]; to throw or cast down; as, to ''abase'' the eye. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#*: ''"Saying so, he '''abased''' his [[lance]]''." - ''[[w:Thomas Shelton|Thomas Shelton]]''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To lower, as in rank, office, condition in life, so as to hurt feelings or cause pain; to depress; to [[humiliate]]; to [[humble]]; to [[degrade]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470)}}<ref name=SOED/>
#*: ''"Whosoever exalteth himself shall be '''abased'''''." - ''Luke 14:11''
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To lower in value, in particular as altering the content of alloys in coins.<ref name=SOED/>{{defdate|Attested from the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>

